  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Old Vine Zinfandel and regular Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Old Vine Zinfandel comes from vines typically 35+ years old, producing more concentrated, complex wines with deeper fruit flavors and better structure. These older vines naturally yield smaller crops, resulting in wines with greater intensity and mineral complexity. Regular Zinfandel from younger vines tends to be fruitier and more straightforward, often with higher yields that can dilute flavor concentration.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose California Zinfandel or Italian Primitivo?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While genetically identical, California Zinfandel typically offers bolder, riper fruit with higher alcohol (14-16%), while Italian Primitivo tends to be more restrained with earthier, mineral-driven profiles and moderate alcohol (12-14%). California expressions emphasize jammy blackberry and spice, whereas Primitivo showcases red cherry, herbs, and Mediterranean terroir. Choose California for power and richness, Primitivo for elegance and food pairing versatility.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What alcohol level should I look for in quality Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The best Zinfandels typically range from 14-15.5% alcohol, offering optimal balance between ripeness and restraint. Wines below 14% may lack the characteristic richness Zinfandel is known for, while those above 16% can become hot and unbalanced. Producers like Ridge, Turley, and Seghesio consistently achieve this sweet spot, delivering concentrated fruit without excessive heat.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Zinfandel good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Zinfandel is excellent for beginners due to its approachable fruit-forward style and food-friendly nature. The grape's natural jammy berry flavors and spice notes are easy to identify and enjoy without extensive wine knowledge. However, beginners should start with moderately-priced bottles ($15-25) from producers like Bogle or 14 Hands to avoid overly tannic or high-alcohol examples that might overwhelm the palate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age premium Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Well-made Zinfandel from top producers can age 8-12 years, with exceptional Old Vine examples lasting 15+ years. Look for wines with good acidity, balanced tannins, and alcohol under 15.5% for aging potential. Producers like Ridge Monte Bello Zinfandel, Turley Estate, and Martinelli have proven track records for age-worthy wines that develop complexity while maintaining their signature spice and fruit character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Zinfandel at 60-65°F (15-18°C), slightly cooler than room temperature but warmer than typical red wine service. This temperature range highlights the wine's spice complexity and fruit concentration while preventing alcohol heat from dominating. If your Zinfandel is high in alcohol (15%+), lean toward the cooler end of this range to maintain balance and drinkability.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes when buying Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Common mistakes include choosing wines with excessive alcohol (16%+) that taste hot and unbalanced, or selecting mass-produced brands that lack terroir expression and complexity. Many buyers also overlook vintage variation in Zinfandel – this grape is particularly sensitive to weather, so research the vintage quality before purchasing. Avoid wines labeled simply as "California" without specific AVA designation, as they're often blended from lower-quality fruit.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Zinfandel if I can't find good options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grenache offers similar berry fruit and spice with typically lower alcohol, while Petite Sirah provides comparable intensity with more structure and tannin. Australian Shiraz shares Zinfandel's bold fruit character and pepper spice, particularly from warmer regions like Barossa Valley. For international options, try French Châteauneuf-du-Pape blends or Spanish Garnacha, which offer similar rustic charm and food-pairing versatility.</p>
